Recommendation
To fortify the risk management capabilities of the Municipal Government and enable it to manage its vulnerabilities in the event of disruptive events, we recommended and Management agreed to:
Institutionalize the PSCP by creating a working group that will prioritize the formulation of the municipal PSCP in accordance with the PSCP guidebook and thereafter submit the plan to the MDRRMO for review, to the LCE for approval, and to the Sangguniang Bayan for the passage of a resolution to institutionalize the PSCP;
Direct the HRMO to further enhance the Municipal Capacity Development agenda by incorporating other mandatory training on Public Service Continuity Planning and ensuring participation of the appropriate LGU officials and personnel in the same; and,
Improve monitoring of operational requirements like the formulation and submission of PSCP to the relevant oversight bodies;

We recommended the Local Chief Executive to:

Require all officials and employees to liquidate their cash advances immediately;
Strictly monitor periodically the submission of liquidation reports to ensure timely accounting thereof to avoid undue accumulation of outstanding cash advances;
Established measures to enforce immediate liquidation of outstanding cash advances to be enacted such as sending demand letter to the accountable officer or effect deduction from salaries/benefits due to the concerned employee;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to exert all efforts to expedite liquidation of cash advances of officers and employees who have resigned or no longer in service; and
Enhance the Municipality’s record keeping and controls through providing sufficient and appropriate storage and IT Infrastructure.

We recommended that:

Municipal Accountant perform a detailed review and analysis of the affected accounts and prepare the necessary correcting journal entry vouchers to have a fair presentation of the accounts in the financial statements and to effect the transfer of completed projects from the CIP accounts to the appropriate PPE accounts and ensure that proper accounts are used in recording transactions;
Municipal Engineer provide the Municipal Accounting Office with copies of the report of completed projects and other necessary documents; 
Municipal Treasurer to update and reconcile inventory records; and
Inventory committee to complete the actual physical count on a specified time frame and submit complete physical inventory report in accordance with Section 124 of the NGAS Manual.

We recommended that onwards, the Local Chief Executive instruct the Municipal Treasurer to:

Ensure the timely and adequate application of fidelity bond requirement before its expiration to ensure that government funds are adequately safeguarded against losses and/or wastage;
Prepare and submit the PIF to determine all the insurable properties of the LGU;
Require the increase of the fidelity bonds of the regular AOs in accordance to the provisions of Bureau of Treasury Circular No. 2-99; and that
Monitor and control the property and cash accountability to ensure proper accounting and recording thereof.

We recommended for the Municipality to coordinate with the provider of the Accounting System and impose the following:

Correct the internal issues presented by the computer system, and make a patch to improve the already existing system;
Request that continuous customer support be easily available whenever issues were presented;
Provide a user manual and incorporate it in the system where any user could access it in case they need help in using the system. If the updating of SL feature is not yet available, then the provider must incorporate it in the system since it is very important in an accounting system; and
Provide safety features in the system. All users of the system and the changes they made must be properly monitored. Users must be provided with certain level of authority as to their capability to access forms, reports, query, and/ or tables.

To strengthen the risk management capabilities of the Municipal Government and enable it to manage its vulnerabilities in the event of disruptive events, we recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) institutionalize the PSCP by creating a working group that will perform the following activities:

to conduct risk assessment; 
to identify critical processes and functions; 
to determine scenarios that may disrupt normal operation; 
to conduct risk analysis and impact analysis; 
to formulate the PSCP based on the identified risks on critical processes and functions and its related steps to be followed to eliminate, if not mitigate, the impact of the determined disruptions following the prescribed template and be guided by the PSCP guidebook; and
to submit plan to the MDRRMO for review,  to the LCE for approval, and to the Sangguniang Bayan for the passage of a resolution to institutionalize the PSCP.

We also recommend that Management should improve their monitoring of operational requirements like the submission of PSCP.

We recommended that management through the:
Sanggunian, Municipal Budget Officer and other responsible offices to prepare and submit Annual Operating Budget (AOB) for each LEEs;
Sanggunian, LFC or Economic Development Officer if any, to deliberate and prepare a 5-year Business Plan (BP) especially with the newly established LEEs;
LFC to conduct semi-annual review and general examination of cost and accomplishments against performance standards.
Management Comment
The management agreed with the recommendation.

